question_body:
Setup for the desired layout  I'm trying to achieve a "framed layout" with a centered page wrapper that has rounded corners and a sticky header using only modern CSS . However, I'm facing potential rendering issues across different browsers.  Describing the specific  layout in words is challenging, so please refer to the screenshots and minimal reproducible example below:   Wrapper (direct child of the <code>body</code> ): Centered with spacing from the screen edges and rounded corners ( <code>border-radius</code> ).  Header: Sticky positioned with <code>position: sticky</code> and <code>top: 0</code> .    To handle the wrapper's rounded corners, I used <code>overflow: clip</code> to hide the overlapping edges of the main content and sticky header while preserving its sticky functionality (AFAIK, <code>overflow: hidden</code> would prevent <code>position: sticky</code> from working). Unfortunately, this approach leads to several issues ...    Issues encountered   Header border-radius clipping:   Chrome: Stays clipped on the top but does not get clipped on the bottom edges.  Firefox: Clipping updates late or only upon interaction (e.g., clicking in the content).  Safari: Works as expected.  Note: Scrolling back to the top sometimes fails to properly clip the header.       <code>backdrop-filter: blur()</code> on the header:  Chrome & Firefox: Delays in updating the clipped border-radius (personal feeling).  Firefox: Does not work ( check this bug ) - removing the <code>border-radius</code> or <code>overflow</code> property of the header's parent element would fix the issue.  Safari: Works as expected.       Attempts to fix   Adding a CSS <code>will-change</code> property with the values <code>scroll-position</code> or <code>transform</code> to the header didn't resolve the issues.  Using a pseudo-element ( <code>header::before</code> ) for the blurred background also didn't work.  I noticed that style recalculations  or  repaints triggered by looping animations or window resize update the clipping correctly.    Minimal, reproducible example    <code>.wrapper {
  overflow: clip;
  border-radius: 20px;
  margin-right: auto;
  margin-left: auto;
  border: 3px solid #7f5af0;
  width: 90%;
}
header {
  position: sticky;
  top: 0;
  -webkit-backdrop-filter: blur(5px);
  backdrop-filter: blur(5px);
  background-color: rgba(44, 182, 125, 0.8);
  height: 100px;
}
/* setup (visual) */
* {
  margin: 0;
  padding: 0;
}
body {
  margin: 2rem;
  min-height: 3000px;
  font-family: sans-serif;
  font-weight: normal;
  line-height: 1.5;
  color: #94a1b2;
  background-color: #16161a;
}
main {
  padding: 1rem 5rem 5rem;
  font-size: 2em;
  background-color: #242629;
}
h1 {
  padding-top: 0.8em;
  font-weight: normal;
  text-align: center;
  color: #fffffe;
}</code>  <code><div class="wrapper">
  <header>
    <h1>Sticky Header</h1>
  </header>
  <main>
    <p>I don't know exactly what to call this design layout. Is there a name for it? "Frame layout", "page within page layout" or "centered page layout"... It's definitely not new in web design, but there are some strange things happening here that I can't explain.<br>My guess is that there are some browser rendering issues going on because of the relatively new CSS properties. I'm aware that I could use some JavaScript to make everything work as aspected, but I want to achieve this design with CSS only.</p>
  </main>
</div></code>    Example also on CodePen   Request for help  Are these issues due to browser (rendering) bugs, or is there a problem with my CSS? Any suggestions for a workaround would be greatly appreciated, but please note that I am looking for a CSS-only solution . Additionally, please provide links to bug reports or spec references if relevant.

answers.body:
Implementing sticky header can be frustrating. There are all kinds of known issues. This got me thinking though if svg masking could solve it in a different way. Hope this helps. (Tested in Chrome and FF).  Update: Added rounded corner support for header (top) and main (bottom).    <code>.wrapper {
  margin-right: auto;
  margin-left: auto;
  position: relative;
  width: 90%;
  min-height: 100%;
}
.wrapper::before {
  content: '';
  background-color: #16161a;
  display: block;
  position: fixed; /* hide overlap */
  top: 0;
  right: 0;
  z-index: 1;
  width: 100%;
  height: 10px;
}
header {
  backdrop-filter: blur(5px);
  background-color: rgba(44, 182, 125, 0.8);
  box-sizing: border-box;
  box-shadow: 20px 20px 0 -10px #7f5af0 inset, -20px 20px 0 -10px #7f5af0 inset;
  clip-path: inset(0 0 10px 0);
  -webkit-mask-image: url('data:image/svg+xml;utf8,<svg preserveAspectRatio="none" xml:space="preserve" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><rect rx="10" x="0" y="0" width="100%" height="100%"/></svg>');
  mask-image: url('data:image/svg+xml;utf8,<svg preserveAspectRatio="none" xml:space="preserve" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><rect rx="10" x="0" y="0" width="100%" height="100%"/></svg>');
  mask-repeat: no-repeat;
  mask-size: 100%;
  padding-top: 8px;
  position: sticky;
  top: 0;
  z-index: 1;
  height: 120px;
  width: 100%;
}
/* round the corners */
header::before, header::after, main::before, main::after {
  content: '';
  display: block;
  position: absolute;
  width: 10px;
  height: 10px;
}
header::before {
  border-top-left-radius: 8px;
  border-top: 4px solid #7f5af0;
  border-left: 4px solid #7f5af0;
  top: 6px;
  left: 6px;
}
header::after {
  border-top-right-radius: 8px;
  border-top: 4px solid #7f5af0;
  border-right: 4px solid #7f5af0;
  top: 6px;
  right: 6px;
}
main::before {
  border-bottom-left-radius: 8px;
  border-bottom: 4px solid #7f5af0;
  border-left: 4px solid #7f5af0;
  bottom: 6px;
  left: 6px;
}
main::after {
  border-bottom-right-radius: 8px;
  border-bottom: 4px solid #7f5af0;
  border-right: 4px solid #7f5af0;
  bottom: 6px;
  right: 6px;
}
/* setup (visual) */
* {
  margin: 0;
  padding: 0;
}
body {
  margin: 2rem;
  min-height: 100%;
  font-family: sans-serif;
  font-weight: normal;
  line-height: 1.5;
  color: #94a1b2;
  background-color: #16161a;
}
main {
  font-size: 2em;
  background-color: #242629;
  box-shadow: 20px -20px 0 -10px #7f5af0 inset, -20px -20px 0 -10px #7f5af0 inset;
  clip-path: inset(10px 0 0 0);
  -webkit-mask-image: url('data:image/svg+xml;utf8,<svg preserveAspectRatio="none" xml:space="preserve" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><rect rx="10" x="0" y="0" width="100%" height="100%"/></svg>');
  mask-image: url('data:image/svg+xml;utf8,<svg preserveAspectRatio="none" xml:space="preserve" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg"><rect rx="10" x="0" y="0" width="100%" height="100%"/></svg>');
  mask-repeat: no-repeat;
  mask-size: 100%;
  margin-top: -20px; /* for clip-paths */;
  padding: 1rem 5rem 5rem;
  z-index: 0;
}
h1 {
  padding-top: 0.8em;
  font-weight: normal;
  text-align: center;
  color: #fffffe;
}
p:not(:last-of-type),
ul {
  margin-bottom: 1em;
}
ul {
  margin-left: 1em;
}
::marker,
code,
a {
  color: #7f5af0;
}
code {
  border-radius: 0.2em;
  padding: 0.1em 0.2em;
  background-color: #16161a;
}</code>  <code><div class="wrapper">
  <header>
    <h1>Sticky Header</h1>
  </header>
  <main>
    <p>I don't know exactly what to call this design layout. Is there a name for it? "Frame layout", "page within page layout" or "centered page layout"... It's definitely not new in web design, but there are some strange things happening here that I can't explain.<br>My guess is that there are some browser rendering issues going on because of the relatively new CSS properties. I'm aware that I could use some JavaScript to make everything work as aspected, but I want to achieve this design with <strong>CSS only</strong>.</p>
    <p>Because of the wrapper's border-radius, I needed a solution to "hide" the overlapping edges of the element boxes. AFAIK, <code>overflow: hidden</code> doesn't work with <code>position: sticky</code>. I came across <code>overflow: clip</code> which achieves (nearly) the same result as hidden but keeps the sticky functionality.</p>
    <p>Unfortunately, I'm encountering some problems across browsers with just this minimal setup (tested in the latest versions of Chrome, Firefox, and Safari):</p>
    <ul>
      <li>Header border-radius clipping:
        <ul>
          <li>Chrome: Stays clipped on the top but does not get clipped on the bottom edges.</li>
          <li>Firefox: Clipping updates late or only upon interaction (e.g., clicking in the content).</li>
          <li>Safari: Works as expected.</li>
          <li>Note: Scrolling back to the top sometimes fails to properly clip the header.</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
      <li><code>backdrop-filter: blur()</code> on the header:
        <ul>
          <li>Chrome & Firefox: Delays in updating the clipped border-radius (personal feeling).</li>
          <li>Firefox: Does not work (<a href="https://stackoverflow.com/questions/74277643/firefox-backdrop-filter-blur-not-working-with-sticky-positioning/76434579#76434579" title="Findings from an answer on Stack Overflow" target="_blank">check this bug</a>) - removing the <code>border-radius</code> or <code>overflow</code> property of the header's parent element would fix the issue.</li>
          <li>Safari: Works as expected.</li>
        </ul>
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p><strong>Note</strong>: At first, I thought that Chrome also just had a delay in updating the clipped border-radius, but I think that some animations that were present on my live page were causing style recalculations or/and repaints and that's why the clipping was sometimes updated in the right moment. Resizing the browser window also updates the "clipping".</p>
    <p>Adding <code>will-change</code> with the values <code>scroll-position</code> or <code>transform</code> to the header didn't fix the issues.
      I tried using a pseudo-element (<code>header::before</code>) to create the blurred background, hoping it would fix the blur problem in Firefox, but it also didn't work.
    </p>
    <p>Now, I'm not sure if all of the described issues are rendering bugs of the mentioned browsers or if my CSS setup is not valid/covered by the spec. I've never had such a specific rendering-related problem before, so I don't know what other solutions might be considered.</p>
  </main>
</div></code>

