Without seeing more of your JavaScript code, it will be difficult to pinpoint the exact issue. Here are a couple likely causes of the problem you described:   You're using <code>position: relative</code> . Unless you're manually adjusting the <code>jotaroX</code> , <code>jotaroY</code> , <code>bombcoliX</code> , and <code>bombcoliY</code> values, they will all have an initial value of <code>0</code> , causing them to always start in collision. You'll likely have better luck with <code>position: fixed</code> for these elements.   You're rotating using the CSS <code>transform</code> property, which doesn't update the <code>height</code> and <code>width</code> . The <code>width</code> will always be <code>150px</code> , even when the image is rotated <code>90deg</code> . You can fix this by calling <code>jotaro.getBoundingClientRect()</code> and using the <code>height</code> and <code>width</code> properties of that.    UPDATE:   You're using global space (distance from top left corner of page) for the player, but local space (distance from top left corner of parent element) for the bomb. Comparing these two will always give incorrect results unless the parent element of the bomb happens to be at the top left corner of the page.   The hit box for your collision detection is the image size, which changes based on the direction the player is moving. This might give you unexpected results.    Following are some updates to your code that fix most of these issues. But first, here are a couple tips that will help you debug things like this in the future:   Try prototyping smaller amounts of code on their own so you can isolate and find bugs quicker. For example, player movement, player animation, collision detection, random placement of bombs, etc. could all be built in their own prototypes with none of the other code getting in the way. When you work the bugs out of each smaller system , you'll have an easier time bringing them all together.  Using <code>alert</code> and <code>console.log</code> is convenient for debugging, but I'd encourage you to try the browser debugging tools if you haven't already. Adding breakpoints and stepping through the code line by line will reveal wrong assumptions and help you find problems quicker.   Best of luck on your journey!    <code>/* Note: I named the character that you control "Jotaro"*/
